EDITORIAL
Student (all For
A Vietnam Moratorium
(The Vietnam Moratorium, n series at national, escniuﬂnt
antique actions, will begin October 15. Students at more than 54»
colleges are already committed to spending the day in ma community with door-indoor campaigns. teach-ins, replies and vlgilI.,
Accompanying the campus-based actions will be organized reports by businessmen, clergymen, community groups and lucia
All activities are directed against United state: action in Vietnam.
The Moratorium has the endorsement oi the National Americans for Democratic Action, the national Student Association, the
New civilization Committee, and the National Democratic coalition.
The following “Student call” has been signed by some 50!
college student body treatments and campus newspaper editors.
A faculty call is being written. The Grlnnell student senate eur
worked the Vietnam Moratorium last Tuesday and allocated fruits
in a Moratorium committee oi the senate and the Grinnell student Movement.)
Ending the war in Vietnam Is the most important task racing
the American nation. Over the last few years, millions of Americans have campaigned, protected. and demonstrated against the
war. Few now defend the war, yet it continues. Death and destruction are animated; boobs and fire continue to advantage
South Vietnam. millions 01 dollars are spent on war while the urgent domestic problems of this country remain unattended. Moreover, the war has lead a corruption inﬂhence on every aspect of
American life, and much of the national respondent can be
travel to It! influence.
The distributed policies of the past which have brought about
this American tragedy have not been changed, We follows the
same military advice which has created a future and bloody conflict while we click to the same policies which have caused the
Paris negotiations to seller. The token displacement of 25,000
troops over a three month period simply is not the substantial
change in policy that is so respiratory needed.
Thus it is necessary for all those who desire peace to become active again and help bring pressure to bear on the present
administration.
We call for a periodic monitoring on "business as usual” in
order that students, faculty members and concerned citizens can
dcvolc time and energy to the important work of taking me issue
of peace in Vietnam to the larger community.
If the war continues this fall and there is no firm commitment [0 American Withdrawal or a associated settlement on OCLO‘
her ls, participating members of the academic community will
spend the entire day organizing against the war and working in
thecommu .uy to get others lo join us in an enhanced and length»
eyed monitoring in November. This process \will continue until
there is American withdrawal or a associated settlement.
We call upon all member oi the university community to
Support the monitoring, and we commit ourselves to organize
this ciiori on our campus and in the larger community. We ask
others to join us.
Michael 1. Brandon
Thomas J. Thomas
